Aer I. So. 1.

Chremes finding Menedemus (the Havton timornmenos) engaged, as he had often noticed him before, in the most laborious operations of the farm, remonstrates with him on the unsuitableness and uselessness of such conduct at his time of life, and by questioning him, draws from him the history of his proceedings. Menedemus says that having by undue severity driven his only son to leave home and go out for a soldier, he has determined to enjoy none of the luxuries, of which his son is deprived, but to punish himself by the most servile work until his son returns.
